# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: dart
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:dart/error-handling] Learn about handling errors and exceptions in Dart.
[src:dart/error-handling] Your Dart code can throw and catch exceptions.
[src:dart/error-handling] Exceptions are errors indicating that something unexpected happened.
[src:dart/error-handling] If the exception isn't caught, the isolate that raised the exception is suspended, and typically the isolate and its program are terminated.
[src:dart/error-handling] In contrast to Java, all of Dart's exceptions are unchecked exceptions.
[src:dart/error-handling] Methods don't declare which exceptions they might throw, and you aren't required to catch any exceptions.
[src:dart/error-handling] Dart provides `Exception` and `Error` types, as well as numerous predefined subtypes.
[src:dart/error-handling] You can, of course, define your own exceptions.
[src:dart/error-handling] However, Dart programs can throw any non-null object—not just Exception and Error objects—as an exception.
[src:dart/error-handling] Catching, or capturing, an exception stops the exception from propagating (unless you rethrow the exception).
[src:dart/error-handling] To handle code that can throw more than one type of exception, you can specify multiple catch clauses.
[src:dart/error-handling] The first catch clause that matches the thrown object's type handles the exception.
[src:dart/error-handling] As the preceding code shows, you can use either `on` or `catch` or both.
[src:dart/error-handling] Use `on` when you need to specify the exception type.
[src:dart/error-handling] Use `catch` when your exception handler needs the exception object.
[src:dart/error-handling] You can specify one or two parameters to `catch()`.
[src:dart/error-handling] The first is the exception that was thrown, and the second is the stack trace (a `StackTrace` object).
[src:dart/error-handling] To partially handle an exception, while allowing it to propagate, use the `rethrow` keyword.
[src:dart/error-handling] To ensure that some code runs whether or not an exception is thrown, use a `finally` clause.
[src:dart/error-handling] To learn more, check out the core library exception docs.
[src:dart/error-handling] During development, use an assert statement— `assert(<condition>, <optionalMessage>);` —to disrupt normal execution if a boolean condition is false.
[src:dart/error-handling] The first argument to `assert` can be any expression that resolves to a boolean value.
[src:dart/error-handling] If the expression's value is true, the assertion succeeds and execution continues.
[src:dart/error-handling] If it's false, the assertion fails and an exception (an `AssertionError`) is thrown.
[src:dart/error-handling] In production code, assertions are ignored, and the arguments to `assert` aren't evaluated.
[src:dart/error-handling] Unless stated otherwise, the documentation on this site reflects Dart 3.12.2.
[src:dart/language-async] Information on writing asynchronous code in Dart.
[src:dart/language-async] Dart libraries are full of functions that return `Future` or `Stream` objects.
[src:dart/language-async] These functions are *asynchronous*: they return after setting up a possibly time-consuming operation (such as I/O), without waiting for that operation to complete.
[src:dart/language-async] The `async` and `await` keywords support asynchronous programming, letting you write asynchronous code that looks similar to synchronous code.
[src:dart/language-async] Code that uses `async` and `await` is asynchronous, but it looks a lot like synchronous code.
[src:dart/language-async] You can use `await` multiple times in an `async` function.
[src:dart/language-async] In `await *expression*`, the value of `*expression*` is usually a Future; if it isn't, then the value is automatically wrapped in a Future.
[src:dart/language-async] This Future object indicates a promise to return an object.
[src:dart/language-async] The value of `await *expression*` is that returned object.
[src:dart/language-async] The await expression makes execution pause until that object is available.
[src:dart/language-async] For an interactive introduction to using futures, `async`, and `await`, see the asynchronous programming tutorial.
[src:dart/language-async] An `async` function is a function whose body is marked with the `async` modifier.
[src:dart/language-async] Adding the `async` keyword to a function makes it return a Future.
[src:dart/language-async] Note that the function's body doesn't need to use the Future API.
[src:dart/language-async] Dart creates the Future object if necessary.
[src:dart/language-async] If your function doesn't return a useful value, make its return type `Future<void>`.
[src:dart/language-async] The value of `*expression*` must have type Stream.
[src:dart/language-async] Execute the body of the for loop, with the variable set to that emitted value.
[src:dart/language-async] Repeat 1 and 2 until the stream is closed.
[src:dart/language-async] To stop listening to the stream, you can use a `break` or `return` statement, which breaks out of the for loop and unsubscribes from the stream.
[src:dart/language-async] For more information about Dart's asynchronous programming support, check out the `dart:async` library documentation.
[src:dart/language-functions] Dart is a true object-oriented language, so even functions are objects and have a type, Function.
[src:dart/language-functions] This means that functions can be assigned to variables or passed as arguments to other functions.
[src:dart/language-functions] You can also call an instance of a Dart class as if it were a function.
[src:dart/language-functions] The `=> *expr*` syntax is a shorthand for `{ return *expr*; }`.
[src:dart/language-functions] The `=>` notation is sometimes referred to as *arrow* syntax.
[src:dart/language-functions] A function can have any number of *required positional* parameters.
[src:dart/language-functions] These can be followed either by *named* parameters or by *optional positional* parameters (but not both).
[src:dart/language-functions] You can use trailing commas when you pass arguments to a function or when you define function parameters.
[src:dart/language-functions] Named parameters are optional unless they're explicitly marked as `required`.
[src:dart/language-functions] When defining a function, use `{*param1*, *param2*, …}` to specify named parameters.
[src:dart/language-functions] When calling a function, you can specify named arguments using `*paramName*: *value*`.
[src:dart/language-functions] To define a default value for a named parameter besides `null`, use `=` to specify a default value.
[src:dart/language-functions] The specified value must be a compile-time constant.
[src:dart/language-functions] If someone tries to create a `Scrollbar` without specifying the `child` argument, then the analyzer reports an issue.
[src:dart/language-functions] You might want to place positional arguments first, but Dart doesn't require it.
[src:dart/language-functions] Wrapping a set of function parameters in `[]` marks them as optional positional parameters.
[src:dart/language-functions] To define a default value for an optional positional parameter besides `null`, use `=` to specify a default value.
[src:dart/language-functions] In Dart 3.13 and later, you can't use modifiers like `final` or `var` for normal function parameters.
[src:dart/language-functions] These keywords are now reserved exclusively for primary constructors to declare instance fields.
[src:dart/language-functions] If you wish to enforce immutability for function parameters, use lints like `parameter_assignments` instead of the `final` keyword in the signature.
[src:dart/language-functions] Every app must have a top-level `main()` function, which serves as the entrypoint to the app.
[src:dart/language-functions] The `main()` function returns `void` and has an optional `List<String>` parameter for arguments.
[src:dart/language-functions] You can use the args library to define and parse command-line arguments.
[src:dart/language-functions] You can pass a function as a parameter to another function.
[src:dart/language-functions] This example uses an anonymous function.
[src:dart/language-functions] You can specify the type of a function, which is known as a *function type*.
[src:dart/language-functions] A function type is obtained from a function declaration header by replacing the function name by the keyword `Function`.
[src:dart/language-functions] Moreover, you are allowed to omit the names of positional parameters, but the names of named parameters can't be omitted.
[src:dart/language-functions] Though you name most functions, such as `main()` or `printElement()`, you can also create functions without names.
[src:dart/language-functions] These functions are called *anonymous functions*, *lambdas*, or *closures*.
[src:dart/language-functions] The following example defines an anonymous function with an untyped parameter, `item`.
[src:dart/language-functions] The anonymous function passes it to the `map` function.
[src:dart/language-functions] The `map` function, invoked for each item in the list, converts each string to uppercase.
[src:dart/language-functions] Then, the anonymous function passed to `forEach`, prints each converted string with its length.
[src:dart/language-functions] If the function contains only a single expression or return statement, you can shorten it using arrow notation.
[src:dart/language-functions] Paste the following line into DartPad and click **Run** to verify that it is functionally equivalent.
[src:dart/language-functions] Dart determines the scope of variables based on the layout of its code.
[src:dart/language-functions] A programming language with this feature is termed a lexically scoped language.
[src:dart/language-functions] You can "follow the curly braces outwards" to see if a variable is in scope.
[src:dart/language-functions] The `nestedFunction()` method can use variables from every level, all the way up to the top level.
[src:dart/language-functions] A function object that can access variables in its lexical scope when the function sits outside that scope is called a *closure*.
[src:dart/language-functions] Functions can close over variables defined in surrounding scopes.
[src:dart/language-functions] In the following example, `makeAdder()` captures the variable `addBy`.
[src:dart/language-functions] Wherever the returned function goes, it remembers `addBy`.
[src:dart/language-functions] When you refer to a function, method, or named constructor without parentheses, Dart creates a *tear-off*.
[src:dart/language-functions] This is a closure that takes the same parameters as the function and invokes the underlying function when you call it.
[src:dart/language-functions] If your code needs a closure that invokes a named function with the same parameters as the closure accepts, don't wrap the call in a lambda.
[src:dart/language-functions] If no return value is specified, the statement `return null;` is implicitly appended to the function body.
[src:dart/language-functions] To return multiple values in a function, aggregate the values in a record.
[src:dart/language-functions] Every property access (top-level, static, or instance) is an invocation of a getter or a setter.
[src:dart/language-functions] A variable implicitly creates a getter and, if it's mutable, a setter.
[src:dart/language-functions] This is why when you access a property, you're actually calling a small function in the background.
[src:dart/language-functions] Reading a property calls a getter function, and writing one calls a setter function, even in cases where the property is declared a variable.
[src:dart/language-functions] However, you can also declare getters and setters explicitly with the `get` and `set` keywords respectively.
[src:dart/language-functions] This allows a property's value to be computed when it's read or written.
[src:dart/language-functions] The purpose of using getters and setters is to create a clear separation between the client (the code that uses the property) and the provider (the class or library that defines it).
[src:dart/language-functions] The client asks for or sets a value without needing to know if that value is stored in a simple variable or calculated on the spot.
[src:dart/language-functions] This gives the provider the freedom to change how the property works.
[src:dart/language-functions] For example, because the value of the property might not be stored anywhere, it could be computed each time the getter is called.
[src:dart/language-functions] Another example is that when a value is stored in a private variable, and public access is only allowed by calling a getter or a setter.
[src:dart/language-functions] The following example showcases this, with the `secret` getter and setter providing indirect access to the private variable `_secret` with its own manipulations on the assigned and retrieved values.
[src:dart/language-functions] When you need to lazily produce a sequence of values, consider using a *generator function*.
[src:dart/language-functions] An external function is a function whose body is implemented separately from its declaration.
[src:dart/language-functions] An external function's implementation can come from another Dart library, or, more commonly, from another language.
[src:dart/language-functions] In interop contexts, `external` introduces type information for foreign functions or values, making them usable in Dart.
[src:dart/language-functions] Implementation and usage is heavily platform specific, so check out the interop docs on, for example, C or JavaScript to learn more.
[src:dart/language-functions] External functions can be top-level functions, instance methods, getters or setters, or non-redirecting constructors.
[src:dart/language-functions] An instance variable can be `external` too, which is equivalent to an external getter and (if the variable is not `final`) an external setter.
[src:dart/language-variables] The variable called `name` contains a reference to a `String` object with a value of "Bob".
[src:dart/language-variables] The type of the `name` variable is inferred to be `String`, but you can change that type by specifying it.
[src:dart/language-variables] If an object isn't restricted to a single type, specify the `Object` type (or `dynamic` if necessary).
[src:dart/language-variables] The Dart language enforces sound null safety.
[src:dart/language-variables] Null safety prevents an error that results from unintentional access of variables set to `null`.
[src:dart/language-variables] The error is called a null dereference error.
[src:dart/language-variables] A null dereference error occurs when you access a property or call a method on an expression that evaluates to `null`.
[src:dart/language-variables] An exception to this rule is when `null` supports the property or method, like `toString()` or `hashCode`.
[src:dart/language-variables] With null safety, the Dart compiler detects these potential errors at compile time.
[src:dart/language-variables] For example, say you want to find the absolute value of an `int` variable `i`.
[src:dart/language-variables] If `i` is `null`, calling `i.abs()` causes a null dereference error.
[src:dart/language-variables] In other languages, trying this could lead to a runtime error.
[src:dart/language-variables] Dart's compiler prevents this error by prohibiting these actions.
[src:dart/language-variables] You must initialize variables before using them.
[src:dart/language-variables] Nullable variables default to `null`, so they are initialized by default.
[src:dart/language-variables] Dart doesn't set initial values to non-nullable types.
[src:dart/language-variables] Dart doesn't allow you to observe an uninitialized variable.
[src:dart/language-variables] This prevents you from accessing properties or calling methods where the receiver's type can be `null` but `null` doesn't support the method or property used.
[src:dart/language-variables] You can't access properties or call methods on an expression with a nullable type.
[src:dart/language-variables] The same exception applies where it's a property or method that `null` supports like `hashCode` or `toString()`.
[src:dart/language-variables] Sound null safety changes potential **runtime errors** into **edit-time** analysis errors.
[src:dart/language-variables] This check allows you to fix these errors *before* deploying your app.
[src:dart/language-variables] Uninitialized variables that have a nullable type have an initial value of `null`.
[src:dart/language-variables] Even variables with numeric types are initially null, because numbers—like everything else in Dart—are objects.
[src:dart/language-variables] You don't have to initialize a local variable where it's declared, but you do need to assign it a value before it's used.
[src:dart/language-variables] Top-level and class variables are lazily initialized; the initialization code runs the first time the variable is used.
[src:dart/language-variables] Often Dart's control flow analysis can detect when a non-nullable variable is set to a non-null value before it's used, but sometimes analysis fails.
[src:dart/language-variables] Two common cases are top-level variables and instance variables: Dart often can't determine whether they're set, so it doesn't try.
[src:dart/language-variables] When you mark a variable as `late` but initialize it at its declaration, then the initializer runs the first time the variable is used.
[src:dart/language-variables] If you never intend to change a variable, use `final` or `const`, either instead of `var` or in addition to a type.
[src:dart/language-variables] A final variable can be set only once; a const variable is a compile-time constant.
[src:dart/language-variables] Use `const` for variables that you want to be **compile-time constants**.
[src:dart/language-variables] If the const variable is at the class level, mark it `static const`.
[src:dart/language-variables] The `const` keyword isn't just for declaring constant variables.
[src:dart/language-variables] You can also use it to create constant *values*, as well as to declare constructors that *create* constant values.
[src:dart/language-variables] You can omit `const` from the initializing expression of a `const` declaration, like for `baz` above.
[src:dart/language-variables] For details, see DON'T use const redundantly.
[src:dart/language-variables] For more information on using `const` to create constant values, see Lists, Maps, and Classes.
[src:dart/language-variables] A wildcard variable with the name `_` declares a local variable or parameter that is non-binding; essentially, a placeholder.
[src:dart/language-variables] The initializer, if there is one, is still executed, but the value isn't accessible.
[src:dart/language-variables] Multiple declarations named `_` can exist in the same namespace without a collision error.
[src:dart/language-variables] Top-level declarations or members where library privacy might be affected are not valid uses for wildcard variables.
